article.description: Chauncey Billups scored 27 points and the Detroit Pistons won for the first time under new coach Larry Brown, beating the winless Miami Heat 93-81 on Friday night.
article.headline: Marlins players only highlight in Miami

images.name: Prince Tayshaun 031031 195x262
images.caption: Odom clanks one more, going 4-for-15 Friday night.

article.linkText: Heat drop to 0-3 with 93-81 loss to Pistons
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Larry Brown won with the Detroit Pistons for the first time, leaving Stan Van Gundy still winless with the Miami Heat. Chauncey Billups scored 27 points and Richard Hamilton added 24, including the Pistons' final 10 points, to help them hold off the Heat 93-81 on Friday night. Brown earned his 880th career victory and his first since being hired in June to replace Rick Carlisle in Detroit. "We had a lot of contributions that made the difference," Brown said. The injury-plagued Heat fell to 0-3 for the first time since 1994. They're alone in last place in the Atlantic Division under Van Gundy, who took over when Pat Riley abruptly resigned last week. "Your job as a coach is to win games," Van Gundy said. "I haven't gotten that done." The Heat's 19,600-seat arena was almost half full for their first home game since Riley stepped down as coach. He remains Heat president, and a team spokesman said Riley was in the building, but he stayed out of public view. The Heat gave fans little to cheer about, falling behind for good less than three minutes into the game. One of the biggest ovations came when several of the World Series champion Florida Marlins were introduced after the first quarter. Billups, who shot 3-for-17 in the Pistons' season-opening loss Wednesday, went 6-for-13 and hit three 3-pointers. "I was just trying to be aggressive," Billups said. "My guys feed off me." Detroit missed its first six shots in the fourth quarter and Miami scored eight consecutive points to close to 76-70. But Billups hit a 3-pointer for an 83-74 lead with 6:25 left to stop the Heat surge. Pistons 18-year-old forward Darko Milicic, No. 2 pick in the June draft, made his NBA debut with 1:23 left. He had two rebounds, two turnovers and a foul. "It felt good," Milicic said. "I'm happy that we won." Ben Wallace had 15 rebounds and four blocks for the Pistons. "We were on the right path tonight," Billups said. "This is what we need to get the season going." The Heat topped 75 points for the first time, but they shot only 36 percent and went 1-for-9 from 3-point range. Perhaps the low point for Miami was when guard Rafer Alston lost track of the 24-second clock and let it run out while dribbling near center court with two minutes left. Heat newcomer Lamar Odom returned after missing all of one game and most of the season opener with a sprained ankle. He shot 4-for-15 and had six turnovers. Miami rookie Dwyane Wade, bothered by a sore hip, played only three minutes in the second half and finished with four points in 23 minutes. The Heat were also without Caron and Rasual Butler, both on the injured list. Undrafted rookie Udonis Haslem was one bright spot for Miami. He had 16 points and 11 rebounds. "I'm going 100 mph," Haslem said. "That's all I know right now." The Heat fell behind 19-8 and were never closer than five points after that. They trailed 22-14 after one period, the fourth time they've scored 15 or less in a period. "This team will hang in there," Van Gundy said. "People will get healthy, and we'll be a good team if we continue to have the disposition we had tonight."

Game Notes: Marlins pitchers Dontrelle Willis and Carl Pavano, center fielder Juan Pierre, shortstop Alex Gonzalez and infielder Lenny Harris took the court for a big ovation after the first quarter. Gonzalez later waved the championship trophy from courtside during a timeout. ... Billups and Hamilton were a combined 15-for-28. They went 6-for-31 in the Pistons' opener.
